Typical American families did not fare as well , nor did those `` wealthy-but-not wealthiest '' families just beneath the pyramid 's top .
As a consequence , starting from November 2008 , several countries launched large `` help packages '' for their economies .
The response of the Federal Reserve , the European Central Bank , the Bank of England and other central banks was immediate and dramatic .
This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market , and the largest monetary policy action , in world history .
By creating $ 600 billion and inserting -LSB- clarification needed -RSB- this directly into banks , the Federal Reserve intended to spur banks to finance more domestic loans and refinance mortgages .
Banks were also investing in foreign currencies , which Stiglitz and others point out may lead to currency wars while China redirects its currency holdings away from the United States .
These bills must now be reconciled .
The New York Times provided a comparative summary of the features of the two bills , which address to varying extent the principles enumerated by the Obama administration .
In many areas , the housing market also suffered , resulting in evictions , foreclosures and prolonged unemployment .
Questions regarding bank solvency , declines in credit availability and damaged investor confidence had an impact on global stock markets , where securities suffered large losses during 2008 and early 2009 .
Economies worldwide slowed during this period , as credit tightened and international trade declined .
Governments and central banks responded with unprecedented fiscal stimulus , monetary policy expansion and institutional bailouts .
Many causes for the financial crisis have been suggested , with varying weight assigned by experts .
Research into the causes of the financial crisis has also focused on the role of interest rate spreads .
Some experts believe these institutions had become as important as commercial -LRB- depository -RRB- banks in providing credit to the U.S. economy , but they were not subject to the same regulations .
However , as market power shifted from securitizers to originators and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power , mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated .
Some believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded .
The majority of these were prime loans .
In addition , an analysis by the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas in 2009 , however , concluded that the CRA was not responsible for the mortgage loan crisis , pointing out that CRA rules have been in place since 1995 whereas the poor lending emerged only a decade later .
Furthermore , most sub-prime loans were not made to the LMI borrowers targeted by the CRA , especially in the years 2005 -- 2006 leading up to the crisis .
Nor did it find any evidence that lending under the CRA rules increased delinquency rates or that the CRA indirectly influenced independent mortgage lenders to ramp up sub-prime lending .
To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes -LRB- in 1995 -RRB- and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising , and does not exonerate the CRA .
Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place .
Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude .
